00:07:44,922 --> 00:07:46,023
I've, of course, lost my voice.

123
00:07:47,064 --> 00:07:47,825
My name is Brittany Albert.

124
00:07:48,085 --> 00:07:49,787
I've been a professional producer in games

125
00:07:49,847 --> 00:07:50,968
for almost nine years now.

126
00:07:52,569 --> 00:07:53,910
I started my career at Fitzel,

127
00:07:53,950 --> 00:07:55,452
primarily working on the John Delife

128
00:07:55,572 --> 00:07:56,713
and Scribblenauts franchises.

129
00:07:57,614 --> 00:07:59,696
I briefly flirted with Free to Play Mobile

130
00:07:59,876 --> 00:08:00,677
at Drop Forge Games.

131
00:08:01,538 --> 00:08:03,599
And I'm currently at City State Entertainment,

132
00:08:04,480 --> 00:08:06,262
overseeing the engineering team

133
00:08:06,522 --> 00:08:09,505
on a PVP-focused MMO called Camelot Unchained.

134
00:08:10,959 --> 00:08:14,320
I'd always had the plan of becoming a programmer in the game industry.

135
00:08:14,960 --> 00:08:18,161
After high school, I preferred my undergrad in computer science.

136
00:08:18,401 --> 00:08:22,623
I was fortunate enough to get an internship one summer where I had an opportunity to work

137
00:08:22,663 --> 00:08:23,563
on game pipeline tools.

138
00:08:24,823 --> 00:08:26,564
But not everything was sunshine and rainbows.

139
00:08:27,224 --> 00:08:29,745
The work just wasn't satisfying.

140
00:08:30,845 --> 00:08:33,146
I felt like I was punching a clock in the morning and evening.

141
00:08:33,906 --> 00:08:38,307
I got some in-the-moment satisfaction through code, but it turns out that my original career

142
00:08:38,347 --> 00:08:39,968
choice wasn't all it was cracked up to be.

143
00:08:41,543 --> 00:08:44,425
In college, I'd work on game projects with other classmates.

144
00:08:44,925 --> 00:08:46,266
In addition to programming, I would

145
00:08:46,286 --> 00:08:48,248
have to wear the producer hat and manage

146
00:08:48,288 --> 00:08:49,228
the scheduling for the team.

147
00:08:50,109 --> 00:08:51,450
And working with my college cohorts

148
00:08:51,470 --> 00:08:53,572
taught me that a producer's job is more than just moving

149
00:08:53,632 --> 00:08:55,473
Post-It notes from left to right on a corkboard.

150
00:08:56,173 --> 00:08:57,735
It's making sure that your team has what

151
00:08:57,755 --> 00:08:59,016
they need to be successful.

152
00:08:59,996 --> 00:09:02,138
It's problem solving, where the problems affect

153
00:09:02,178 --> 00:09:04,339
the people you care about most and see every day,

154
00:09:04,820 --> 00:09:06,161
and the people who are giving their all

155
00:09:06,201 --> 00:09:07,001
for the sake of the game.

156
00:09:08,307 --> 00:09:12,773
So sure, production can be summed up as kind of like cat hurting, but ultimately it's about

157
00:09:12,813 --> 00:09:15,416
being the person who cares most about the well-being of the team.

158
00:09:16,057 --> 00:09:19,762
Simply put, the team builds the game, the producer builds the team.

159
00:09:21,725 --> 00:09:23,186
So at the conclusion of my internship,

160
00:09:23,526 --> 00:09:25,988
I made the realization that while I loved solving programming

161
00:09:26,028 --> 00:09:28,909
problems, I got so much more satisfaction out

162
00:09:28,949 --> 00:09:30,770
of helping people make games that they are proud of.

163
00:09:31,351 --> 00:09:33,452
So after lots of school and a pile of debt,

164
00:09:33,552 --> 00:09:35,133
I decided I wasn't going to be a programmer.

165
00:09:36,353 --> 00:09:37,694
Maybe you've had this thought too

166
00:09:37,814 --> 00:09:39,675
about changing the direction of your career,

167
00:09:40,716 --> 00:09:42,917
whether it's changing from one discipline to another,

168
00:09:43,457 --> 00:09:45,338
entering the game industry from another industry,

169
00:09:45,819 --> 00:09:47,520
or going into a management role after being

170
00:09:47,540 --> 00:09:48,540
an individual contributor.

171
00:09:49,637 --> 00:09:52,140
Society often sees changing a previously made decision

172
00:09:52,200 --> 00:09:54,723
as a very negative trait, so we tend to shy away against it.

173
00:09:55,785 --> 00:09:57,307
I'm here today to tell you how to do it,

174
00:09:57,687 --> 00:09:58,808
so it's far less scary.

175
00:10:00,130 --> 00:10:02,894
First off, prepare yourself to ask a lot of questions,

176
00:10:03,214 --> 00:10:05,437
starting with, why are you thinking

177
00:10:05,457 --> 00:10:06,358
about changing your career?

178
00:10:07,325 --> 00:10:10,786
Maybe your interests have changed and you don't want to do the same thing forever. A

179
00:10:11,166 --> 00:10:16,588
change of pace is nice. Uh maybe your current path isn't for you. Whether you just don't

180
00:10:16,628 --> 00:10:21,350
see yourself in it long term, uh you don't like where you're at or you just don't have any

181
00:10:21,390 --> 00:10:26,391
future prospects. Maybe your decision is financial. You might want to make more money

182
00:10:26,431 --> 00:10:31,093
than you currently are. Conversely, uh you may be shying away from jumping because you

183
00:10:31,133 --> 00:10:35,555
can't necessarily take a pay cut. Before making the switch, I'm going to talk a little bit

184
00:10:36,772 --> 00:10:40,053
Ask yourself, do I need a new role or just a new job?

185
00:10:40,754 --> 00:10:42,455
Is it the environment that's not working for you

186
00:10:43,095 --> 00:10:43,775
or the work itself?

187
00:10:44,616 --> 00:10:47,177
Maybe you're just not feeling the game you're working on.

188
00:10:48,017 --> 00:10:49,558
Maybe the game you're working on is awesome,

189
00:10:50,038 --> 00:10:51,359
but the team could be more supportive.

190
00:10:52,039 --> 00:10:55,181
Maybe the team is amazing, but your boss is a total asshole.

191
00:10:56,582 --> 00:10:58,263
Changing career path isn't going to fix that.

192
00:10:59,682 --> 00:11:02,524
So is there something keeping you from changing your mind?

193
00:11:03,464 --> 00:11:05,526
I resisted becoming a producer for a long time

194
00:11:05,566 --> 00:11:07,488
because a lot of classmates in college would say,

195
00:11:07,508 --> 00:11:08,849
oh, of course you're gonna be a producer

196
00:11:08,889 --> 00:11:10,290
because girls aren't very good at programming.

197
00:11:11,971 --> 00:11:13,972
And I wanted to stay in engineering

198
00:11:14,012 --> 00:11:14,973
so I could prove them wrong.

199
00:11:15,574 --> 00:11:18,176
But proving someone wrong is great in the moment,

200
00:11:18,196 --> 00:11:20,457
but that's not going to provide me long-term satisfaction.

201
00:11:21,798 --> 00:11:23,780
So you've asked yourself all these questions

202
00:11:24,120 --> 00:11:25,921
and you're still like, yeah, I'm gonna take the jump.

203
00:11:26,382 --> 00:11:27,242
So how do you do it?

204
00:11:28,190 --> 00:11:29,090
Set goals for yourself.

205
00:11:29,831 --> 00:11:32,973
Define a positive meaning and definition of success.

206
00:11:34,674 --> 00:11:37,175
Develop realistic expectations for what

207
00:11:37,195 --> 00:11:38,076
it is you're trying to do.

208
00:11:38,596 --> 00:11:40,337
For me, this was starting out producing

209
00:11:40,357 --> 00:11:42,398
a small engineering team.

210
00:11:42,798 --> 00:11:44,179
And if I could do that successfully,

211
00:11:44,259 --> 00:11:46,260
I wanted to branch out to disciplines I didn't know

212
00:11:47,501 --> 00:11:49,702
very well, like design and art and audio.

213
00:11:50,723 --> 00:11:55,264
Eventually, I ended up leading production on a full title, but that doesn't happen overnight.

214
00:11:55,965 --> 00:11:59,886
Setting an unobtainable goal at the beginning may not give you the positive reinforcement

215
00:11:59,926 --> 00:12:01,547
you need to keep yourself going along.

216
00:12:03,547 --> 00:12:08,549
It is critical that you find a mentor in what it is you want to do so you have a person

217
00:12:08,569 --> 00:12:10,710
you can ask for advice as you chart your new territory.

218
00:12:11,530 --> 00:12:16,052
If you can, find a mentor in your gender, race, or sexual orientation because there

219
00:12:16,072 --> 00:12:17,612
will be unique challenges that you'll face.

220
00:12:19,439 --> 00:12:21,280
It may not be wise to jump right in.

221
00:12:22,161 --> 00:12:24,042
Go on a trial run before you can make the leap.

222
00:12:24,342 --> 00:12:26,283
Verify that your initial interest in a new path

223
00:12:26,323 --> 00:12:27,264
could pan into something,

224
00:12:27,884 --> 00:12:29,405
or if you should even go that route at all.

225
00:12:30,646 --> 00:12:32,227
One way to do this is to ask your manager

226
00:12:32,247 --> 00:12:33,848
to try out some of the responsibilities

227
00:12:33,868 --> 00:12:35,048
your new position would entail.

228
00:12:35,849 --> 00:12:37,190
We once had a programming intern

229
00:12:37,250 --> 00:12:38,510
who had an interest in production,

230
00:12:39,011 --> 00:12:41,332
and she had asked if she could spend two weeks

231
00:12:41,792 --> 00:12:44,474
shadowing producers, and those two weeks taught her

232
00:12:44,574 --> 00:12:46,275
she in no way wanted to be a producer.

233
00:12:48,329 --> 00:12:50,951
Be flexible, know that you might have to add extra work

234
00:12:50,971 --> 00:12:53,232
to your current responsibilities in order to try this out.

235
00:12:53,872 --> 00:12:55,513
Know that it might not be a clean transition

236
00:12:55,593 --> 00:12:56,313
into your new role.

237
00:12:56,714 --> 00:12:59,475
Be prepared to train your replacement leaving a new role.

238
00:12:59,515 --> 00:13:01,636
You are taking on a lot of work in this scenario.

239
00:13:03,117 --> 00:13:05,258
And with all of that, things might still go wrong.

240
00:13:05,778 --> 00:13:06,599
You might fail.

241
00:13:07,199 --> 00:13:09,040
But success at anything is really hard

242
00:13:09,160 --> 00:13:11,481
and you can't fail if at first you didn't try something.

243
00:13:12,485 --> 00:13:13,827
you will have to pay your dues again.

244
00:13:14,528 --> 00:13:15,809
Regardless of what you did before,

245
00:13:15,829 --> 00:13:18,193
you now have to prove yourself in a new role.

